Air BNB Project

Introduction

An AirBNB, otherwise known as Air Bed and Breakfast, is a unique service that allows property owners anywhere in the world to rent out their property to travelers in search of a place to stay. Rather than worry about booking an expensive hotel with many rooms for each guest, an AirBNB can be a convenient alternative, as guests can book an entire house, a private room, or a shared room. AirBNBs are located nearly everywhere in the United States, but one of the main places where they can be found is in New York City, as this is one of the most popular cities in the country. Although this unique service can be a great alternative to a hotel, the prices of these AirBNBs may vary based on its characteristics. Things such as the room type, location, and amount of nights can drastically affect the price of an AirBNB, especially in a major city such as New York City. This project is looking to be able to predict the price of an AirBNB in New York City based on its characteristics.

Methods

EDA and Data Clean

To begin the analysis, an exploratory data analysis was conducted. Each variable within the data set was analyzed to make initial hypotheses and access their usability. The variables of ‘id’, ‘name’, ‘host_id’, ‘last_review’, and ‘last_review’ were first analyzed for their unique values. For each of these variables, nearly each observation had its own unique categorical level, as the output generated over 1000 unique observations. There also appears to be many NA values for these variables, which would be extremely difficult to impute, as these variables are so unique. These variables appeared to be insignificant anyways, as they appeared to have been used to organize the data set, meaning that they would not be useful for predicting price. Therefore, these variables were omitted from the generated models later in the report. The variable of ‘room type’ was next analyzed by generating a bar graph to visualize its distribution. It appeared that ‘Entire home/apt’ and ‘private room’ each had over 10,000 observations, while ‘shared room’ barely had any observations in comparison to the previous two. This was extremely interesting, as ‘Entire home/apt’ and ‘private room’ would most likely lead to a more expensive price, meaning that this variable is most likely extremely useful in predicting price. This variable was then transformed into a factor variable, as this is much more useful for analysis. Next, the variable of ‘neighborhood group’ was analyzed by once again generating a bar graph to view its distribution. It appeared that ‘Brooklyn’ and ‘Manhattan’ included most observations, while ‘Staten Island’, ‘Bronx’, and ‘Queens’ did not include many observations. This is very interesting, as different neighborhoods in New York City have differing price ranges. This variable was also transformed into a factor, as this would be more beneficial for analysis. The variables of longitude and latitude were then analyzed utilizing the summary function and boxplots. The distributions for both of these variables appeared to be extremely condense, as both of their maximum and minimum values were within 0.5 of each other. This is very interesting, as the observations may belong in different neighborhoods, but are extremely close from a latitude and longitude perspective. Next, the variable of ‘minimum nights’ was analyzed utilizing the summary function and generating a boxplot. The average minimum nights was 7.056, but the boxplot appeared to show many outliers, some ranging up until 1250 nights. This was very interesting, as the longer you stay, the more expensive it would be. The variable of ‘number of reviews’ was next analyzed in the same way. Both the boxplot and summary function displayed a wide range of observations, ranging from 0 to 650, while the average was around 23. The variable of ‘availability_365’ also displayed a large distribution that was much less, showing that the different properties’ availabilities span over the entire year. For the variables of ‘reviews_per_month’ and ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, both the boxplots and summary functions also display an extremely skewed distribution, emphasizing that these variables span over a large range. From there, the variable of ‘reviews_per month’ was further examined. When analyzing this variable, there appeared to be 7008 missing values in the training data set. Since it was numeric, MICE imputation with 5 iterations was utilized to impute the missing values for this variable. There were also 3044 missing values for this variable in the test data set. MICE was once again utilized to impute those values.

Methods for Analysis

To begin the analysis, a linear model was generated to predict price that included the variables of ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘neighbourhood’, ‘latitude’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, ‘reviews_per_month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, and ‘availability_365’. From there, an anova test was conducted to see which variables appeared to be significant in the general linear model. Next, a reduced linear model was created that only included the significant variables from the first linear model. This model was then submitted as the first set of predictions to understand the baseline score of having a linear model. Next, a LASSO model was created to help with variable selection to predict the price of the AirBNB. Once again, this included the variables of ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘neighbourhood’, ‘latitude’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, ‘reviews_per_month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, and ‘availability_365’. This method is extremely useful, as it takes ridge regression and other methods a step further by conducting variable selection. In order to conduct the LASSO model, the ideal value for lambda would make the model perform the best. To find the best lamda, cross validation was conducted by plotting the values and selecting the minimum value for lambda. From there, the method of Random Forests was then utilized to predict price. The variables included in this analysis once again included ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘neighbourhood’, ‘latitude’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, ‘reviews_per_month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, and ‘availability_365’ Three different random forests were generated, each with a different number of trees. Each random forest was then analyzed and each was submitted as its own set of predictions. The results of these analyses are in the following section of this report.

Analysis

Linear Models

To begin the analysis, a linear model was first generated that included the variables of ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘neighbourhood’, ‘latitude’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, ‘reviews_per_month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, and ‘availability_365’. With this model, an ANOVA analysis was conducted to assess the significant variables within the linear model. From this analysis, it appeared that the variables of ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘neighbourhood’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, and ‘availability_365’ were extremely significant in predicting price. Next, a reduced linear model was generated that only included the significant variables shown in the ANOVA test. However, there were many errors with the ‘neighbourhood’ variable within this model, as the number of levels in the test data set differed from the number of levels in the training data set. Therefore, this variable was decided to be excluded from the reduced linear model. The final reduced linear model included the variables of ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, and ‘availability_365’. This model was then submitted as the first set of predictions on the kaggle website. This submission generated a score of 0.70561, which is not very strong. Therefore, we can see that a basic linear model is not best suited for predicting price in this dataset.

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.36.28 PM.png")

ANOVA of full linear model

LASSO

Next, the LASSO method was conducted for variable selection to help predict the price of an AirBNB in New York City. The variables that were considered included ‘neighbourhood_group’, ‘neighbourhood’, ‘latitude’, ‘longitude’, ‘room_type’, ‘minimum_nights’, ‘number_of_reviews’, ‘reviews_per_month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, and ‘availability_365’. To conduct the LASSO model in he correct fashion, the ideal lambda value must be calculated through cross validation. This was conducted by utilizing the ‘cv.glmnet’ function in R and choosing the minimum lambda value on the plot of the log(lambda) vs. the MSE. Therefore, the best lambda value was 0.607005, which is shown from the minimum value on the graph. From there, the LASSO model was constructed utilizing this optimized lambda value. The coefficients of this model were then printed to understand which variables it chose to be significant in predicting price. From the printed coefficients, it appears that the variables of ‘neighborhood group’, ‘room type’, ‘minimum nights’, ‘number of reviews’, ‘reviews per month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, ‘availability_365’, and ‘longitude’ are significant in predicting the price. The variable of neighborhood seemed to be converted to a dummy variable, with each neighborhood being its own separate predictor. Within these variables, although many neighborhoods were insignificant, the majority of them were, meaning it should be included in the significant variables. Although longitude was significant, it appeared that latitude was not significant in predicting price, which was extremely interesting. Therefore, the significant variables selected from the LASSO Model included ‘neighborhood group’, ‘neighborhood’, ‘room type’, ‘minimum nights’, ‘number of reviews’, ‘reviews per month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, ‘availability_365’, and ‘longitude’.

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.39.10 PM.png")

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.39.43 PM.png")

Some significant coeffients from LASSO

Random Forest

Based on these selected variables, a Random Forest analysis was then conducted to try to predict the price of an AirBNB. Three separate random forests were generated: one with 100 trees, one with 250 trees, and one with the default 500 trees. Each random forest was then analyzed and submitted as predictions to the kaggle website. When looking at the random forest with 100 trees, it calculated the mean of squared residuals as 45829.16, as well as the percent of variance explained as 16.64%. This random forest was then utilized to predict on the test data set, and those predictions were submitted to kaggle. From this submission, the score was equal to 0.49898, which is pretty good. Therefore, we can see that the random forest model is performing much better with the significant variables selected from LASSO than the linear model performed. When looking at the random forest with 250 trees, it calculated the mean of squared residuals as 45303.49, as well as the percent of variance explained as 17.6%. This random forest was also utilized to predict on the test data set, and those predictions were submitted to kaggle. From this submission, the score was equal to 0.44408, which was slightly improved from the random forest with 100 trees. Next, a random forest with 500 trees (the default number) was generated. This model calculated the mean of squared residuals as 45223.35, as well as the percent of variance explained as 17.74%. Although this model appeared to have been the best based on the mean of squared residuals and percent of variance explained, it had its predictions submitted to kaggle, which produced a score of 0.45222, which was worse than the random forest with 250 trees. Therefore, it can be concluded that the random forest with 250 trees performed the best out of all the models

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.44.57 PM.png")

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.47.17 PM.png")

Conclusions/ Future Work

In conclusion, it appears that random forests are the strongest way to predict the price of an AirBNB in New York City. When utilizing a reduced linear model that was fitted based on an ANOVA test from the full model, the model produced a very mediocre score, while also disregarding some variables that were proven to be significant when conducting different methods. When conducting a LASSO model, which is great for variable selection, the variables of ‘neighborhood group’, ‘neighborhood’, ‘room type’, ‘minimum nights’, ‘number of reviews’, ‘reviews per month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, ‘availability_365’, and ‘longitude’ are extremely significant in predicting the price of an AirBNB in New York City. These significant variables were proven to be greatly useful when fitting a random forest, as this proved to be the strongest method for prediction and produced the best scores. Although the random forests were the strongest method in predicting the price, adjusting the number of trees utilized in the random forest would generate varying scores. Although a random forest with 500 trees produced a very respectable score, a tree with only 100 trees slightly improved the score, while a tree with 250 trees produced a score of 0.44408 . Therefore, it can be concluded that a random forest with 250 trees and the predictors of ‘neighborhood group’, ‘neighborhood’, ‘room type’, ‘minimum nights’, ‘number of reviews’, ‘reviews per month’, ‘calculated_host_listings_count’, ‘availability_365’, and ‘longitude’ appeared to be the strongest method in predicting the price of an AirBNB in New York City, as this model produced the best score. While the methods conducted produce a very respectable score, there is still much future work that can be done. The variable ‘name’ was dropped at the beginning of the analysis, as it produced too many unique categorical values. However, in the future, one could attempt to extract specific words from each name, such as ‘luxury’, ‘penthouse’, etc, that could be directly correlated with the price of the property. It also could have been useful to attempt different methods, such as a GAM or KNN to explore how to predict the price. The variable of last review could maybe have also been utilized to extract the year, as a property who has not had a review for years might be cheaper than one who is still receiving reviews. In conclusion, a random forest with 250 trees that contain the significant variables chosen from LASSO produced a very respectable score, but could always be improved.

Rain Project

Introduction

Various weather data for Australia was given from the dates November 2, 2007 to June 25, 2017. Given this data set, we were tasked in building an accurate predictive model in order to model whether it will rain the day after, or the rain_tomorrow variable. We were given many different metrics, including wind direction, humidity, pressure, and whether or not it rained during that day for the given date. We explored model building with random forest, boosting, and bagging.

Methods

EDA andd Data Clean

Initially, a lot of data cleanup was done on the dataset in order to make use of various variables. First, all the categorical variables were transformed into factor variables using as.factor(). Then, for the variable date, since it would have too many levels as a categorical variable as is, it was split into three separate factor variables known as Year, Month, and Day. This allowed for retaining some of the information that was captured by the initial date variable, while transforming it to a more usable format. After ensuring each variable was in its correct format, there were still a lot of missing values to account for. Initially, we utilized the package HMisc in order to impute mean values for all the numeric missing values, and mode for all the categorical missing values. After imputation, another variable known as air_density_3pm was created utilizing the variables humidity_3pm and pressure_3pm. This was done after conducting some research on weather predictions, and finding that air density was a strong predictor of future rain chances. Knowing this, and having the variables needed to calculate air density, we decided to implement this variable utilizing the following formula: air_density <- (train\(pressure3pm*100) /((train\)temp3pm+273.15)*rd), where rd = 287.058, or the specific constant for dry air.

Methods for Analysis

Random Forest

After our data was cleaned and usable, we utilized a random forest in order to model the probability of rain_tomorrow, utilizing all the variables except for ID, Date, Evaporation, and Sunshine. As discussed earlier, the date variable was split up into three variables that retained it’s information. We also dropped ID because there really was no significance assigned to the variable, as it was just an indicator for keeping track of the data. Evaporation and Sunshine on the other hand, were more of an interesting decision. We decided not to include these variables in our model due to the vast amounts of missing data in these columns. These variables came with 33775 and 33566 NAs, respectively. This is out of a dataset that contained 34191 observations. While we did impute these variables, we decided that since the values for the variables were overwhelmingly missing, including them in our random forest model just did not make enough sense. The addition of the variables in the model would add an immense amount of variance that would cause a high risk of overfitting.

Boosting

In addition to our random forest, we also made a gradient boosting machine. For the boosted model, we utilized the same training data set that we used for the random forest, as many of our justifications for dropping certain variables from our models still held for our boosted model. Utilizing the package xgboost, we built a validation and test data set on our training data before ultimately testing our final model on Kaggle. We also utilized the xgb.plot.importance function in order to obtain a plot of variables that were most important in the boosted model.

Bagging

We also used a bagging model to try and fit the data using the ipred package. The model was built on a training data set that omitted the variables date, evaporation, id, sunshine, cloud9am, and cloud3pm. The variables cloud9am and cloud3pm were omitted in this training data set because they had a significantly high number of NA values. They were omitted in this model instead of the others because although they had a high number of NA values, they did not have as many in proportion to the other columns omitted. Omitting them in this model also allows us to assess how significant they are in lowering our final log loss. Our bagging model used 100 bootstrap replications.

Results

Random Forest

Our initial results utilizing the random forest yielded some interesting results. Our overall log loss error after turning the random forest was pretty good at 0.34549. However this mark was improved upon later by our boosted model and our bagging models. With our random forest, the most important variable by far was found to be humidity_3pm. This variable had by far the highest decrease in the GINI index, as shown in figure 1. In addition to humidity_3pm, the random forest also indicated that variables location and pressure were among the most important variables of the model.

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.57.27 PM.png")

XGBoost

In our XGboost model, the accuracy we obtained utilizing the validation set approach was 85.6 percent, which indicated that this model was pretty good at predicting if it would rain. This is seen in the confusion matrix which is seen in Figure 4. These results were further validated when we uploaded our predictions to Kaggle, where we obtained a log loss error of 0.3045 for the test data set. This was a substantial improvement over the random forest model, which had a log loss error of 0.34549. When taking a look at the variable importance plots for our XGboost model, we found that variable humidity_3pm to be by far the most important variable. Following that, variables pressure_3pm and wind_gust_speed were the most important variables for our boosted model.

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 10.59.19 PM.png")

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 11.05.08 PM.png")

Bagging

In our bagging model, our overall log loss error was 0.34922. This is slightly higher than the log loss error of 0.3045 and 0.34549 we got for random forest and XGboost, respectively. Similar to the other models, the most important predictors for rain tomorrow were humidity at 3pm, the day, and wind direction at 3pm. This can be seen also in Figure 4. Having the variables cloud9am and cloud3pm omitted did in fact appear to contribute to a decrease in model accuracy, thus confirming that we should instead use the variables with imputed data to predict tomorrow’s rainfall.

knitr::include_graphics("Screen Shot 2021-12-14 at 11.01.06 PM.png")

Conclusions / Future Work

In conclusion, our results strongly pointed to humidity at 3pm being far and away the most important predictor variable when trying to predict rainfall in Australia. Both our boosted model and our random forest had this variable being the most significant predictor for rain_tomorrow. This makes sense, as higher levels of humidity indicates higher levels of moisture in the air. This explains why it is so significant in predicting if it will rain in the following day, as higher levels of moisture in the air would tend to indicate a greater possibility for rain. Something that we expected to have more of an impact in our models, but ultimately did not was our calculated air density variable. This utilized humidity and pressure at 3 pm, both variables that were found to be among the most important in our boosted model, in order to make a new variable air density. However, despite our initial thoughts, air density just simply did not appear to be important in any of our models. Location also was a very important variable in our random forest model, which also made a lot of sense. Areas that tend to have more humidity and climates that facilitate rainfall will tend to have more precipitation than areas with more dry climates.

Overall, our final boosted model had the highest level of prediction accuracy with a log loss error of 0.30458. We were pretty satisfied with this score, as our boosted model was much better than the naive model of 0.69, so we were successful in building a pretty accurate rainfall predictor model.

For future work, we would probably explore the variables found to be most significant like humidity, location and pressure more in depth. Taking a look at how one could use these variables in particular to build an accurate model would be the next step, because our results indicate that a few variables have the most pull in predicting rainfall. We believe one could build a pretty accurate model with far less variables than we utilized in our models, as our results point towards a select few variables being the important predictors in rainfall.
